<HL>
   California May Sharply Curtail Business
   Of First Capital Holdings' Unit Today
   ----
   By David B. Hilder and Frederick Rose
   Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/10/91
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A3
</SO>
<CO>
   AXP FCH
</CO>
<MS>
FINANCIAL (FIN)
</MS>
<IN>
DIVERSIFIED FINANCIAL SERVICES, CREDIT INSTITUTIONS (FIS)
LIFE INSURANCE (INL)
INSURANCE (INS)
</IN>
<RE>
CALIFORNIA (CA)
NEW YORK (NY)
</RE>
<LP>
   California insurance regulators are expected as early as
today to sharply curtail the operations of one of troubled
First Capital Holdings Corp.'s major life insurance units,
according to people familiar with the company.
   It is believed that the action will likely be followed by
a conservatorship, in which California regulators formally
take control of the company and all its operations.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   First Capital won't resist California Insurance
Commissioner John Garamendi's plan to issue cease and desist
orders barring the unit, First Capital Life Insurance Co.,
from honoring policyholders' redemption requests and from
selling new policies, those familiar with the situation said.
   The expected orders would halt an apparently increasing
demand for policy redemptions that strip the company of its
cash and can compel the sale of assets at fire-sale prices.
The bar on new business is widely seen as a formality, since
few new policies are being sold these days.
   The regulatory orders would be the second major action
taken by California regulators in the past month against a
junk bond-laden insurance company. On April 11, Mr.
Garamendi's department seized First Executive Corp.'s
Executive Life Insurance Co. unit, in the largest insurance
failure ever.
   Industry observers noted that cease and desist orders can
be more quickly carried out than a conservatorship. A
conservatorship is expected to follow because it is harder to
restore policyholder rights of redemption without the
complete regulatory control that conservatorship gives
insurance regulators.
   The exact timing of Mr. Garamendi's expected move couldn't
be determined. One person familiar with discussions among Mr.
Garamendi, First Capital and its advisers said his order is
expected today or Monday. Another such person predicted the
order will come "very soon" but declined to be more specific.
   A spokesman for First Capital Life said the company "is
exploring all our options to best protect policyholders'
investments" but wouldn't elaborate. A spokesman for Mr.
Garamendi declined to comment, as did a spokesman for
American Express Co., which owns 28% of First Capital
Holdings.
   First Capital Life had invested assets of $4.1 billion at
Dec. 31. First Capital Holdings' other major life insurance
unit, Virginia-based Fidelity Bankers Life Insurance Co., had
invested assets of $4.0 billion. It isn't known whether
Virginia regulators will take any action, although industry
observers say it is likely to follow California's actions
closely.
   The immediate peril to the First Capital units has been
demands by policyholders to redeem their investments. It is
believed that redemption demand -- already strong in the
weeks since Executive Life was taken over by regulators --
soared this week, after it was disclosed that California
regulators were negotiating with American Express for a
rescue of First Capital.
   First Capital's spokesman declined to disclose the amount
of redemption requests. However, he said "the numbers have
been increasing and any increase is a matter of concern." He
added that requests have been "manageable."
   Still, First Capital's woes go deeper than the recent jump
in redemption demand. As with Executive Life, the First
Capital units suffered from plunging junk-bond investments.
About 40% of First Capital's invested assets are in such
high-yield securities.
   The market value of First Capital Holdings bonds at year's
end was $692 million less than the $5.73 billion at which the
securities were carried on the company's books. First
Capital's spokesman said the market value of those bonds has
improved by $187 million since the end of the year.
   Several officials involved in the First Capital rescue
talks say First Capital's portfolio isn't as troubled as
First Executive's, largely because First Capital tended to
buy bonds with better claims on issuing companies' assets and
avoided bonds that don't pay cash interest.
   Salomon Brothers, which is representing First Capital
Holdings and evaluated First Executive's portfolio for
regulators, has said it can sell $1 billion of First
Capital's junk bonds for no net loss or gain, according to
people familiar with the talks. A Salomon official declined
to comment.
   The main effort to bolster First Capital's financial
foundation came with Mr. Garamendi's request that American
Express shore up the company, but those talks haven't
produced any results yet.
   Besides its own First Capital Holdings shares, American
Express is concerned about the insurer's fate largely because
stockbrokers at its Shearson Lehman Brothers Inc. securities
unit sold their customers thousands of insurance policies and
annuities issued by First Capital Life.
   First Capital Holdings has tried to raise cash by selling
a portion of First Capital Life's insurance business that
amounts to about $1.3 billion of assets. Advisers to First
Capital have said that some action by regulators might make
it easier to sell part or all of First Capital Life by
stopping the recent rush of policyholder withdrawals.
</TEXT>
