<HL>
   American Express, California in Talks
   To Prop Up Struggling First Capital
   ----
   By David B. Hilder
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/06/91
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4
</SO>
<CO>
   AXP FCH
</CO>
<MS>
FINANCIAL (FIN)
</MS>
<IN>
DIVERSIFIED FINANCIAL SERVICES, CREDIT INSTITUTIONS (FIS)
LIFE INSURANCE (INL)
INSURANCE (INS)
</IN>
<RE>
CALIFORNIA (CA)
NEW YORK (NY)
</RE>
<LP>
   American Express Co. is talking with the California
insurance commissioner about ways to prop up First Capital
Holdings Corp., a struggling insurance company in which
American Express owns a 28% stake, according to people
familiar with the talks.
   The talks between officials of American Express and John
Garamendi, the California insurance commissioner, have been
going on for about two weeks, and began with a meeting that
included Mr. Garamendi, American Express Chairman James D.
Robinson III and Howard L. Clark Jr., chairman of Shearson
Lehman Brothers Inc., American Express's securities unit. Mr.
Garamendi and Mr. Clark are scheduled to meet again today in
New York, people familiar with the discussion said.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mr. Garamendi's interest in having American Express
bolster First Capital could indicate that the Los Angeles
insurance company's problems are more serious than First
Capital has indicated. In March, defaults on junk bonds in
its investment portfolio forced First Capital to revise its
fourth-quarter financial results to a loss of $24.7 million,
or 53 cents a share. The company had previously reported net
income of $10.2 million, or 22 cents a share, in the period.
First Capital said it would try to sell some of its insurance
business and its long-time chairman resigned.
   For Mr. Garamendi, the problems of First Capital come on
the heels of his seizure last month of the largest insurance
unit of Los Angeles-based First Executive Corp., which also
was hurt by its big holdings of junk bonds. Mr. Garamendi is
trying to find a rescuer for the First Executive unit,
Executive Life Insurance Co. of California, while New York
regulators are seeking a buyer for another unit, Executive
Life Insurance Co. of New York.
   First Capital has invested a substantial part of its $8
billion of assets into high-risk, high-yield junk bonds. In
the past, First Capital has reported that about 23.5% of its
assets are in securities rated below investment grade. But
new reporting rules for insurance companies are likely to
increase that amount.
   American Express is concerned about the fate of First
Capital largely because Shearson stockbrokers sold their
customers thousands of insurance policies and annuities
issued by First Capital's main unit, First Capital Life
Insurance Co. If First Capital Life becomes insolvent,
Shearson would most likely face some lawsuits and many angry
customers.
   American Express has proposed buying from First Capital
the insurance business that involves Shearson customers, or
taking over the management of that business and guaranteeing
that Shearson customers won't incur losses on their policies,
people familiar with the talks said. It isn't clear whether
those proposals will satisfy Mr. Garamendi's concerns.
   Officials at American Express, the California Insurance
Department and First Capital declined to comment. First
Capital shares closed at $2.25 on Friday, up 25 cents, in New
York Stock Exchange composite trading.
   For Shearson, the negotiations with Mr. Garamendi
represent an unwelcome reminder that the process of digesting
problems created in its massive expansion of the late 1980s
aren't yet over. Many of First Capital's annuities and
policies were originally sold by stockbrokers at E.F. Hutton
&amp; Co., which Shearson acquired after the 1987 stock market
crash. First Capital Life also was once a Hutton unit.
   Insurance industry executives say First Capital's woes
stem from its promise of relatively high interest rates on
annuities and insurance policies and its failure to raise
capital to support its growth.
</TEXT>
</DOC>

