<HL>
   First Capital
   Unit Blocked
   By Regulators
   ----
   By Frederick Rose
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/13/91
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A3
</SO>
<CO>
   AXP CCI FCH
</CO>
<MS>
FINANCIAL (FIN)
</MS>
<IN>
MAJOR MONEY CENTER BANKS (BAN)
ALL BANKS, BANKING NEWS AND ISSUES (BNK)
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
DIVERSIFIED FINANCIAL SERVICES, CREDIT INSTITUTIONS (FIS)
LIFE INSURANCE (INL)
INSURANCE (INS)
SECURITIES (SCR)
</IN>
<NS>
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
</NS>
<RE>
CALIFORNIA (CA)
NEW YORK (NY)
VIRGINIA (VA)
</RE>
<LP>
   LOS ANGELES -- California regulators clamped down on
operations at the largest insurance unit of First Capital
Holdings Corp., amid growing questions about the medium-sized
insurer's sudden plunge and the risk of major losses to
policyholders.
   The effects of the regulatory order rippled widely Friday,
in the latest woes to surface about a junk bond-laden
insurance company. Worries that regulators would dump the
company's junk bonds prompted a slump in the bond market,
which in turn triggered a wave of computer-guided stock sales
orders.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   California's regulatory step, which had been anticipated,
echoed at American Express Co., which said it will take a
$144 million pretax charge in the current quarter,
representing all of a 28% stake in Los Angeles-based First
Capital Holdings held by American Express's Shearson Lehman
Brothers Inc. unit. There were also negative implications for
Citicorp's Citibank unit, the leader of a $275 million
syndicated loan to First Capital Holdings.
   Beleagered First Capital Holdings stock shed nearly a
third of its value in Friday's tumbling stock markets,
falling 43.75 cents to close at 93.75 cents in composite
trading on the New York Stock Exchange. American Express
stock slid 87.5 cents a share, to close at $23.875 on the Big
Board.
   California Insurance Commissioner John Garamendi, in a
cease and desist order, declared First Capital Life Insurance
Co., the unit of First Capital Holdings, to be in "hazardous"
financial condition and barred all policy redemptions and
loans. He also barred the company from writing any new
business. First Capital Life will continue to pay ordinary
policyholder claims, including death and annuity benefits.
   The order, issued Friday in Los Angeles, was agreed to by
the company, which said the halt to redemptions would help
"stablilize" financial conditions at First Capital.
   Mr. Garamendi said his action was impelled by an
unexpected explosion in redemption demands from policyholders
after a disclosure of his demands that American Express and
Shearson Lehman bolster First Capital's financial base. From
an average of about $10 million a day two weeks ago,
redemption requests surged to $25 million last Monday, $30
million on Tuesday, $60 million on Wednesday, and $100
million on Thursday. Redemption requests that were in process
won't be paid as long as regulatory curtailments are in
effect.
   First Capital Life, based in San Diego, is one of two
major units of First Capital Holdings. It had assets of $4.46
billion at Dec. 31, about 190,000 policyholders and 93,000
annuitants in 49 states. The other major unit, Fidelity
Bankers Life Insurance Co., based in Richmond, Va., had
assets of $4.07 billion at Dec. 31, with about 120,000
policyholders and 105,000 annuitants. In all, the two
companies have more than $31 billion of insurance liabilities
payable over many decades.
   A spokesman for Virginia's Bureau of Insurance said the
state agency is keeping a close watch on Fidelity Bankers and
is in contact with California regulators. He said the company
currently is "in good standing" with regulators and meets
legal capital requirements.
   Mr. Garamendi, announcing the cease and desist order, said
that Gerry R. Ginsberg, president and chief operating officer
of First Capital Holdings, was removed from oversight of the
First Capital Life unit and that First Capital Life's
president, Fred Arthur Buck, will report directly to Richard
K. DeScherer, acting chairman of First Capital Holdings.
   First Capital, with about 40% of its investments in
high-yield investments, is the second major junk bond-laden
insurer to come under regulatory control in California in the
past month. It's roughly half the size of First Executive
Corp.'s Executive Life Insurance Co. unit, seized by
regulators on April 11. Mr. Garamendi said that First
Capital's financial problems aren't as severe as those of
First Executive's units.
   Although he asserted that First Capital has serious
problems, Mr. Garamendi announced a series of measures that
he said cure the company's woes, among them the sale of a
part of the company's business, a search for added capital,
and a program to sell the company's junk bonds -- which
sparked Friday's swoon in the bond market. "We believe
policyholders will receive 100% of contracted benefits," he
told reporters.
   But analysts were far less assured of a happy outcome and
speculated that there may be a "black hole," in the words of
one, of prospective losses. Among other things, the failure
of American Express or Citicorp to recapitalize the troubled
insurer concerned observers. Based on public numbers, such a
recapitalization would by one estimate require between $100
million and $200 million -- a relatively small sum for these
institutions, if it fixed the problem.
   "I have to wonder whether there's something that I just
don't know here and which the public hasn't been told," said
Ray Dirks, an analyst at Baird, Patrick &amp; Co., who has in the
past recommended the stock of First Capital Holdings.
American Express and Citicorp declined to comment on the
failure, to date, of their rescue talks with Mr. Garamendi.
   But a number of signs point to crumbling foundations at
First Capital Holdings and its units. Although the company
posted net income for 1990 of $7 million, or 15 cents a
share, on revenue of $980.7 million, its bond and real estate
investments showed marked weaknesses.
   A particular concern with analysts is the company's bond
portfolio, consisting not only of junk bonds, but in many
cases ones for which there is no active market. The so-called
"market value" of the insurer's bonds was about $700 million
less than the value at which they were carried on the
company's books at Dec. 31 -- a gap almost twice the $383.8
million in shareholder equity at that date.
   However, only about 10% of the company's $7.48 billion in
short-term and long-term securities was valued by market
quotes. Market values for the rest were determined by various
"statistical services" and "internal methods," according to
the company's annual filing with the Securities and Exchange
Commission.
   While the company's junk bond problems predominate, there
are other serious weaknesses. Some 12% of the company's $275
million mortgage loan portfolio has interest more than 90
days overdue or is in foreclosure proceedings -- more than
twice the insurance industry average.
   American Express's $144 million charge is likely to
produce a second-quarter loss at its Shearson Lehman Brothers
securities unit. And American Express may face additional
future costs from its association with First Capital. About
three-quarters of the policies and annuities issued by First
Capital's California insurance unit (formerly E.F. Hutton
Life Insurance Co.) are held by Shearson customers -- a
potential legal liability if First Capital Life fails.
   American Express has resisted Mr. Garamendi's demands that
it inject capital into First Capital Life but says it is
still "in discussions" with the commissioner.
   First Capital's problems also mean bad news for Citibank,
which last year led the syndicate that lent $275 million to
First Capital Holdings. Friday's cease and desist orders
block the flow of cash between First Capital Life and its
parent. Some bankers have said that Citibank still holds most
of the $275 million loan because few other banks were willing
to buy portions of the debt. Citicorp declines to say how
much of the loan it still holds or whether it has reserved
against a potential loss on the loan.
   ---
   David B. Hilder in New York contributed to this article.
</TEXT>
