<LEADPARA>  Shearson Lehman Brothers is negotiating with California insurance regulators,
trying to head off a potential failure of First Capital Life Insurance Co.,
which has more investments in "junk bonds" than other insurers still
operating, people who have been briefed on the talks said Sunday.;    Shearson
is the largest seller on Wall Street of First Capital's policies and owns 28
percent of the company, whose parent is based in Los Angeles.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  SHEARSON OFFERS PLAN TO AVERT FAILURE OF
CALIFORNIA INSURER  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     It is expected to offer two different approaches, either taking over
management of the insurer's portfolio, guaranteeing more than $2 billion that
backs the policies, or buying back all the universal life policies that
Shearson sold.;    That offer is expected to be discussed today when Howard
Clark Jr., chairman and chief executive of Shearson, meets in Manhattan with
John Garamendi, California's first elected insurance commissioner.;    A
spokesman for Shearson declined to comment Sunday. Calls to the California
Insurance Department and First Capital were not answered.;    First Capital
has retained Salomon Brothers to examine ways to shore up its finances, which
were crippled with the collapse of the junk bond market last year.;   
Executives involved in the situation said Salomon was exploring at least two
options with First Capital, including the sale of its universal life business
or the sale of a large number of the insurance company's junk bonds in the
open market.;    Both moves, if successful, would help First Capital's
troubled financial position.;    These executives said at least two potential
buyers for the universal life business had held discussions with Salomon,
although their names could not be immediately determined.;    A Salomon
spokesman did not return a telephone message Sunday.;    The scramble to deal
with First Capital comes amid increasing concerns about the health of some
U.S. insurance companies.;    Last month, California regulators seized control
of Executive Life Insurance Co., a subsidiary of First Executive Corp.;   
Executive Life was then the insurance company with the largest portfolio of
junk bonds. Garamendi, who oversaw the seizure, said the company was in a
hazardous financial condition, primarily because of defaults and the declining
values in its junk bond portfolio.;    A recent accounting change also has
hurt First Capital. As a result of the change, which affects how insurance
companies define junk bonds, First Capital, which reported last year that 20.2
percent of its assets were in junk bonds, has increased that figure to 40.7
percent.;    The negotiations between Shearson and California regulators are a
result largely of the Wall Street firm's ill-fated acquisition in 1988 of E.F.
Hutton &amp; Co. Hutton ran an insurance company, called E.F. Hutton Life, which
it sold in 1987 to First Capital Holdings, the parent of First Capital Life.; 
  When Shearson bought Hutton, it acquired a 44 percent interest in First
Capital Holdings, whose products the firm began to market.  </TEXT>
