<HL>
   Little Progress
   Is Made in Talks
   On First Capital
   ----
   By David B. Hilder
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/07/91
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A11
</SO>
<CO>
   AXP CCI FCH
</CO>
<MS>
FINANCIAL (FIN)
</MS>
<IN>
MAJOR MONEY CENTER BANKS (BAN)
ALL BANKS, BANKING NEWS AND ISSUES (BNK)
DIVERSIFIED FINANCIAL SERVICES, CREDIT INSTITUTIONS (FIS)
INSURANCE (INS)
</IN>
<RE>
CALIFORNIA (CA)
NEW YORK (NY)
</RE>
<LP>
   California's insurance commissioner and American Express
Co. made little progress in their talks about a possible
rescue of First Capital Holdings Corp., amid signs that the
commissioner may soon take action against First Capital's
main unit.
   The commissioner, John Garamendi, met in New York
yesterday with Howard L. Clark Jr., chairman of American
Express's Shearson Lehman Brothers Inc. securities unit.
According to people familiar with the talks, Mr. Garamendi
expressed reservations about plans proposed by Shearson that
would aid Shearson clients who bought policies from a unit of
First Capital, a Los Angeles-based insurance holding company.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mr. Garamendi is seeking a solution that would help all
policyholders of First Capital, which has been hurt by its
large investments in the high-risk, high-yield securities
called junk bonds. First Capital had $747 million in paper
losses on its $3.15 billion junk bond portfolio at year end
and $120 million of paper losses on other investments,
according to a filing with the Securities and Exchange
Commission.
   Mr. Garamendi had originally asked New York-based American
Express to put cash into First Capital, but American Express
has rebuffed that suggestion, according to people familiar
with the talks.
   Mr. Garamendi is also talking with officials of Citicorp,
whose main unit was the lead bank in a $275 million loan to
First Capital last year.
   First Capital, which is 28% owned by American Express, has
about $8 billion in assets and is roughly half the size of
Los Angeles-based First Executive Corp., which last month
became the largest U.S. insurance holding company to fail,
also because of losses on junk bonds. If regulators have to
take control of First Capital's insurance units, one of
several possible actions, it will add significantly to a
burden of insurance insolvencies that is already the largest
in history.
   Although Mr. Garamendi is continuing to talk to both
American Express and Citicorp about First Capital's problems,
he is concerned that publicity about First Capital's woes
could lead to an increase in requests from policyholders to
withdraw their funds, people familiar with the discussions
said.
