<LP>
   LOS ANGELES -- California regulators yesterday formally
seized control of First Capital Life Insurance Co. after
senior creditors sought to have the parent, First Capital
Holdings Co., put into involuntary bankruptcy.
   The bankruptcy petition by Citibank and other creditors
wasn't expected and appears to have interrupted California
Insurance Commissioner John Garamendi's efforts to revitalize
First Capital Life without a complete takeover.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In response to the bankruptcy petition, Mr. Garamendi
yesterday entered an order of conservation against First
Capital Life, giving the California insurance department full
operating control over the company. Mr. Garamendi said he
took the formal action to protect policyholders from
uncertainties created by the creditors' bankruptcy petition.
   On Friday, Mr. Garamendi had instituted narrower
cease-and-desist orders against the company, barring policy
redemptions and loans but affirming normal payments of death
benefits and annuities.
   In an interview, the California insurance commissioner
said he has been in talks with Citibank and American Express
Co., holder of a 28% stake in First Capital Holdings. "We
knew that it was possible that there might be a bankruptcy
filing when we cut {the holding company's} air hose off" with
the cease-and-desist order. "But now it's going to be a lot
more work and responsibilities."
   Citibank's motives for the petition weren't entirely
clear. The bank said only that its action was "an attempt to
protect the bank group's rights." As recently as last
Thursday, people familiar with Citibank sought to minimize
First Capital's troubles and said the company wasn't
delinquent in its obligations under the loan agreement.
   The petition for involuntary bankruptcy under Chapter 11
of the U.S. Bankruptcy Code was filed by Citibank, a unit of
New York-based Citicorp, as agent for a $275 million
syndicated credit agreement. The filing in federal court in
Los Angeles asserted that $120 million is due and outstanding
under a term loan and that about $11.6 million is due as
reimbursements of payouts under a letter of credit.
   It's believed that Citibank is owed about $175 million of
the $275 million loan total. Citibank put its portion of the
First Capital loan on non-performing status, according to
people familiar with the discussions. The step's actual
impact on second-quarter earnings will depend on whether and
how much Citicorp sets aside as a provision for possible
losses on the loan.
   Citibank's filing, supported by two other members of the
banking group, Mitsui Manufacturers Bank and National
Westminster Bank, says the loan is secured by stock in
various units of First Capital Holdings, including First
Capital Life and Fidelity Bankers Life Insurance Co., which
was taken over Monday by Virginia regulators.
   A spokesman for First Capital Holdings and its
subsidiaries said the Los Angeles-based company was
"considering its options" and that the company believed the
California insurance commissioner's formal takeover of First
Capital Life "was the best way to protect the policies of our
customers."
   First Capital Holdings has 20 days to respond to
Citibank's court request for involuntary bankruptcy.
   Some observers speculated that the petition may have been
filed to forestall any temptation by California and Virginia
regulators to grab holding company assets in satisfaction of
insurance-company debts. Among other things, the holding
company has about $30 million in cash. With the petition in
place, any such transactions would be subject to court
scrutiny.
</TEXT>
