<LEADPARA>  A dispute between Shearson Lehman Brothers and California insurance regulators
intensified Tuesday, with the state's insurance commissioner contending that
the Wall Street firm had a responsibility to infuse First Capital Life
Insurance Co. with more capital.;    The struggling insurance company has more
investments in "junk bonds" than any other insurer still independently
operating.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Business  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  GARAMENDI URGES SHEARSON TO SHORE UP AILING
FIRST CAPITAL  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     Shearson, which owns 28 percent of the insurer's parent, has been the
largest seller on Wall Street of the company's policies and contracts.;    The
dispute comes after more than two weeks of negotiations between the California
regulators and executives of Shearson and its parent, American Express Co. On
Monday, those talks broke down when the regulators rejected proposals by
Shearson to protect its own customers who had purchased First Capital
products. John Garamendi, California's insurance commissioner, was said to be
seeking a more comprehensive solution to the problem.;    In statements
Tuesday, Garamendi said that the financial problems of First Capital appeared
to be extensive, and that both Shearson and American Express needed to take
action to handle the entire problem, rather than protecting only their
customers.;    "Our continuing review" of the First Capital Life Insurance
Company "indicates that the company needs a substantial infusion of cash,"
Garamendi said. "This is Shearson Lehman's and American Express'
responsibility.";    He added that the position in First Capital had been
purchased "so that they would have annuities and life insurance products to
sell through their financial consultants, and sell they did.";    Garamendi
said that from 1986 through the first quarter of this year, more than 75
percent of First Capital's business was produced by Shearson or American
Express employees.;    He said that, in that time, the two companies
"generated more than $3 billion worth of First Capital business. Meanwhile,
the percentage of non-investment grade assets of First Capital grew from less
than 15 percent to more than 40 percent of total assets." A recent accounting
rule change was responsible for much of that change, increasing the junk bond
holdings First Capital reported from 20.2 percent of its assets to 40.7
percent.;    Garamendi said he believed that both Shearson and American
Express should make sure that First Capital was viable, and referred to
American Express's well-known advertising campaign.;    "If membership has its
privileges, than ownership has its responsibilities," he said.  </TEXT>
