<LP>
   Virginia regulators seized Fidelity Bankers Life Insurance
Co., the second major unit of beleaguered First Capital
Holdings Corp. to be curbed by regulators in less than a
week.
   The action by Virginia's Bureau of Insurance blocks all
policy redemptions and loans but permits routine payments of
death and annuity benefits, as well as accident and health
claims.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Fidelity Bankers, based in Richmond, Va., had assets of
about $4.07 billion at Dec. 31, and about 213,000 life
insurance policies and 97,000 annuitants.
   The unit is slightly smaller than First Capital Life
Insurance Co., based in San Diego, whose business was sharply
curbed by California regulators on Friday. First Capital Life
had assets of $4.46 billion at Dec. 31, about 190,000
policyholders and 93,000 annuitants. Both companies have
substantial holdings of junk bonds.
   Virginia's move puts substantially all of First Capital
Holdings' insurance business under regulatory restrictions.
Together, Fidelity Bankers and First Capital Life, have more
than $31 billion in life insurance benefits owed to
policyholders over the coming decades.
   Although industry watchers had expected Virginia
regulators to swiftly follow California's action, a Virginia
Bureau of Insurance spokesman said Friday that Fidelity
Bankers was in "good standing" and that the company met
minimum capital requirements. The spokesman, Kenneth Schrad,
said he didn't know what had occurred between Friday and
yesterday to change the Bureau's view.
   Fidelity Bankers said it was cooperating with Virginia
regulators, adding that it believed the step was in the best
interest of policyholders.
   Much of the business of First Capital Life and Fidelity
Bankers was written through securities dealers, who were
major sellers of annuities written by both companies, opening
the potential for substantial legal liability at various
brokerage companies.
   The Shearson Lehman Brothers securities unit of American
Express Co., with a 28% stake in First Capital Holdings,
based in Los Angeles, sold business that brought in some
$1.74 billion of premiums in the last three years at the two
companies, according to a Securities and Exchange Commission
filing. PaineWebber Inc. accounted for business that brought
in $641.9 million over the same period.
   American Express and Shearson Lehman have said they are
continuing talks with California insurance regulators. As
previously reported, American Express said it will take a
$144 million pretax charge in the current quarter,
representing the 28% stake. Also there are negative
implications for Citicorp's Citibank unit, leader of a $275
million syndicated loan to First Capital Holdings. A
PaineWebber spokeswoman declined to comment on the company's
sales -- believed to have been written largely with Fidelity
Bankers.
   Separately, Moody's Investors Service Inc. and Standard &amp;
Poor's Corp. said they downgraded First Capital Holdings
Corp.'s subordinated debt.
</TEXT>
