<LP>
   NEW YORK -- American Express thought it got out of the
risky part of the insurance business two years ago when it
sold its last common shares of Fireman's Fund.
   But American Express has found a new way to lose money in
a California insurance company. This time it's First Capital
Holdings, a struggling life insurer of which American Express
once owned 44%, now reduced to 28%. Many Wall Street analysts
think it's unlikely American Express will emerge unscathed
from its association with First Capital, and they have begun
estimating how bad the pain will be.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   First Capital owns the former E.F. Hutton life insurance
company. Customers of American Express's Shearson Lehman
Brothers unit, including many acquired when the firm bought
Hutton in 1988, hold about $2.8 billion of First Capital
policies and annuities.
   Insurance regulators are looking hard at First Capital and
its two insurance units, which invested heavily in junk
bonds, bank loan participations, and commercial real estate.
The California insurance commissioner is expected to sharply
restrict the operations of First Capital's California
insurance unit in a matter of days. This week the
commissioner publicly called on American Express to pump cash
into the unit, but American Express is balking.
   Analysts' estimates of potential charges against American
Express's earnings begin at around $200 million and run as
high as $430 million. While that's manageable for a company
of American Express's size and cash flow, it is likely to
produce a second consecutive quarter of weak earnings and
could force the company to raise more capital, perhaps by
selling common stock.
   The First Capital woes come at a bad time. American
Express's charge-card business is under competitive attack.
First-quarter profit of its charge card and travelers check
unit fell 25%.
   Analysts are lowering their 1991 earnings estimates, and
at least one, Frank DeSantis of PaineWebber Inc., has
downgraded American Express to a rating of "unattractive"
from "neutral."
   The problem, Mr. DeSantis believes, is that write-offs
related to First Capital could wipe out much of Shearson's
capital. Because Shearson needs good credit ratings to
continue its activities in the capital markets, American
Express would probably bow to pressure from ratings agencies
to shore up Shearson with more cash.
   The pain could start with the First Capital stake, still
on American Express's books at $144 million though its market
value is below $20 million. If insurance regulators seize
control of the insurance units, American Express will have to
write off its investment, analysts say; they put the profit
impact at 20 cents to 30 cents a share.
   A tougher question is how much it might also cost American
Express to prop up First Capital's California insurance unit,
the seller of nearly all the policies held by Shearson
customers, or to make up potential losses to Shearson
clients. Early estimates of those costs run from $50 million
to nearly $300 million. James P. Hanbury at Wertheim Schroder
says "no more than $50 million or $100 million." Mr.
DeSantis's estimate is $280 million, or about 10% of the
value of the First Capital policies held by Shearson
customers. (He uses 10% because the market value of First
Capital's year-end assets was some 10% below book value.)
   In response to those estimates, a Shearson spokesman said,
"We are confident that First Capital Life currently has the
resources to repay clients at least their original
investments. Shearson now views any guarantees as open-ended
commitments, which it is not in a position to make."
   John Garamendi, the California insurance commissioner,
won't say how much cash he thinks American Express should put
into First Capital. But people familiar with the talks say he
privately asked for $60 million. Several officials involved
in the First Capital rescue talks say First Capital's
portfolio isn't as junky as that of First Executive, another
junk-bond-laden California insurance concern whose main unit
Mr. Garamendi seized last month.
   Jack Byrne, a newly elected American Express director who
is credited with turning around two troubled insurers, Geico
and Fireman's Fund, thinks Mr. Garamendi is taking too hard a
line. "My understanding is that American Express made a
number of very reasonable proposals to try to help the
situation," he says, "and I find it hard to understand why
the insurance commissioner has not worked with them a little
more."
   The next few quarters could be rocky for American Express,
but fans believe its stock, which closed at $24.75, up 50
cents, in New York Stock Exchange composite trading
yesterday, will rise along with the economy. "If American
Express is successful in defending its franchise and we get a
recovery in the economy and their basic business, then it
could go much higher," says Mr. Hanbury. Adds Allerton
Cushman Jr. of Morgan Stanley, who began calling the stock a
buy in mid-March at around 26: "Prospects for the stock
appear to be more clearly linked to a consumer economic
recovery than ever before."
