<LP>
   California insurance commissioner John Garamendi turned up
the heat on American Express Co. to prop up its 28%-owned
First Capital Holdings Corp., saying that "If membership has
its privileges, then ownership has its responsibilities."
   The commissioner has been talking for two weeks with
executives of New York-based American Express and its
Shearson Lehman Brothers Inc. securities unit about ways to
rescue the Los Angeles insurer but has made little progress.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   First Capital needs a "substantial infusion of cash" and
"this is Shearson Lehman/American Express's responsibility,"
the commissioner said. "They bought First Capital so that
they would have annuities and life insurance products to sell
through their financial consultants, and sell they did." From
1986 through the 1991 first quarter, more than three-quarters
of the business of First Capital's California insurance unit
was generated by Shearson.
   Despite Mr. Garamendi's strong language, American Express
didn't budge from its previous position that it is interested
in helping only clients of its Shearson Lehman Brothers unit
and not other policyholders of First Capital.
   In New York, Shearson said: "Shearson has presented the
commissioner with a number of alternatives that have been
developed out of a commitment to protecting the interests of
its clients who are First Capital Life policyholders. The
commissioner is looking to develop a more comprehensive
solution. We recognize and respect his position regarding
developments at First Capital. Discussions with the
commissioner are continuing."
   First Capital's woes are likely to hurt American Express
financially even if the financial services concern doesn't
bow to Mr. Garamendi's demand that it pump cash into First
Capital.
   At a minimum, analysts say, American Express will soon
have to write down the value of its First Capital stake.
American Express carries the stake on its books at its
original cost of $144 million, even though First Capital
shares have plunged. At yesterday's closing price, the value
of that stake stood at about $14.6 million.
   The commissioner made his remarks while in Washington to
testify before the Senate Commerce Committee about another
troubled Los Angeles insurer, First Executive Corp., which
like First Capital has been crippled by large investments in
high-risk, high-yield "junk bonds." Mr. Garamendi seized
First Executive's largest insurance unit last month, the
biggest failure yet of a U.S. insurer.
   He didn't rule out a similar fate for First Capital, which
has about $8 billion in assets and is roughly half the size
of First Executive. "As we pursue our discussions, we will
continue to closely monitor First Capital, and will take any
action necessary to best protect the interests of
policyholders," he said. Mr. Garamendi's remarks were seen as
unusally strong, particularly given his earlier reluctance to
publicize First Capital's problems for fear that
policyholders would try to cash in their policies or take out
loans on them, equivalent to a run on a bank.
   A spokesman for First Capital said the level of policy
surrenders "has increased, and it is a matter of concern,"
but added that "it's still at a manageable level."
   If Mr. Garamendi takes control of First Capital's main
insurance unit or if American Express adds cash to First
Capital or its insurance unit, then American Express will
have to write down the value of its original investment and
deduct that amount from its earnings.
   Such a write-down also will reduce the capital base of the
Shearson Lehman Brothers unit, and rating agencies may put
pressure on American Express to put more cash into Shearson,
analysts said. If Shearson clients incur losses on First
Capital policies, Shearson may face demands to make up the
difference, creating an additional drag on earnings and
capital.
   "The uncertainty that creates may put pressure on the
company to put more capital into Shearson because of the
rating agencies," said Frank DeSantis, an analyst at
PaineWebber Inc.
   If American Express pumps cash into First Capital and
takes greater control of the company, American Express
wouldn't have to deduct that amount from its earnings. It
will simply be a transfer of capital from American Express to
an affiliate.
   The First Capital spokesman conceded Mr. Garamendi's
remarks were "a very strong public statement" but declined to
speculate on why he made them. He added, "Any negotiations
that would lead to greater capital are certainly helpful."
   Mr. Garamendi is also talking with officials of Citicorp,
whose main unit was the lead bank in a $275 million loan to
First Capital last year.
   First Capital's stock has fallen steadily since news of
the Garamendi talks was reported Monday. The stock, which
ended last week at $2.25, plummeted 87.5 cents yesterday in
New York Stock Exchange composite trading to $1.125. American
Express closed at $25.125, down 12.5 cents.
   Standard &amp; Poor's Corp. cut its rating on First Capital's
$120 million of subordinated debt to triple-C-plus from
double-B-minus. Claims-paying ability ratings for First
Capital Life Insurance Co. and Fidelity Bankers Life
Insurance Co. fell to double-B from triple-B-plus. The
ratings remain on S&amp;P's CreditWatch, with implications
changed to "negative" from "developing."
</TEXT>
