<LEADPARA>  First Capital Holding Corp., reeling after a $770 million first-quarter loss
and the seizure of its two primary insurance units, is headed for bankruptcy
court, published reports said today.;    First Capital, which reported the
huge loss Monday, plans to file for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection from its
creditors, the Los Angeles Times and The Wall Street Journal reported.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Business  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  FIRST CAPITAL REPORTED NEAR CHAPTER 11  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     First Capital spokesman Charles Perkins declined to say when the company
would file, noting the firm still has some assets, including an insurance
company in Britian.;    In its earnings report, First Capital reported a loss
from continuing operations of $2.3 million, or 5 cents a share, in the first
quarter.;    The rest of the $770 million loss was the result of the firm's
writing off of the net assets of its two insurance subsidiaries, which were
seized by regulators in California and Virginia.;    The first quarter losses
from San Diego-based First Capital Life Insurance Co. and Richmond, Va.-based
Fidelity Bankers Life Insurance Co. amounted to $768 million or $16.44 per
share.;    The company earned $16.1 million, or 35 cents a share, for the
quarter ending March 31, 1990.;    California regulators seized First Capital
Life in an effort to prevent the parent company's creditors -- including
Citibank -- from forcing it into bankruptcy. Citibank leads a consortium that
loaned First Capital $275 million last year.;    Insurance Commissioner John
Garamendi said he took the steps to protect First Capital policy holders.;   
If the holding company files for bankruptcy protection, "it would not affect
the assets of the insurance company," said Tom Epstein, deputy California
insurance commissioner.;    The company "is a protective wall and insurance
policy holders would suffer no adverse impact," he said.;    The insurers were
awash in junk bond investments, whose value plunged in recent years.;   
Garamendi said recently that policy holders and annuitants with companies held
by First Capital were likely to receive 100 cents on the dollar on their
policies and investments.  </TEXT>
