<DESCRIPT>  INSURANCE; COMPANY; BAN; STATE; REGULATION; ORGANIZATION  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  State regulators Friday ordered a $4.5 billion insurance company to stop
writing new policies, saying its overdose on junk bonds has nearly killed it.;
   State Insurance Commissioner John Garamendi's action means San Diego-based
First Capital Insurance Co. will no longer honor requests from customers who
have rushed to cash in $265 million worth of policies.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Business  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  STRICT RULES ON FIRST CAPITAL
INSURER ORDERED TO STOP WRITING NEW LIFE
POLICIES  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Additional information attached to the end of this article  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     "The action I have taken is intended to stabilize and begin the process of
rehabilitating the company," Garamendi told a capitol news conference. "It
will give us the necessary time to develop a long-term strategy to return the
company to financial health.";    190,000 policies nationwide;  First Capital
Life, whose most prominent stockholder is Shearson Lehman Brothers, has issued
190,000 life insurance policies nationwide.;    But Garamendi said junk bonds
grew from 16 percent of its investment portfolio in 1986 to 46 percent in
1991, and it had operating expenses roughly twice the industry's average.;   
"First Capital Life's problems are serious and require immediate attention,"
Garamendi said.;    The state's intervention, which comes about a month after
state regulators seized major portions of junk bond-dependent insurer First
Executive Corp., means First Capital cannot make payments to its parent
company or its affiliates without state approval.;    'The time we need';  The
company issued a three-paragraph statement Friday in which it said the state's
action will give it "the time we need to stabilize the company's finances and
assure long-term value of our customers' policies.";    "While we regret the
company has reached this point; we believe it was in the best interest of our
policyholders to take this step.";    As news of the company's shaky financial
status spread in recent weeks, Garamendi said, requests to cash in policies
grew from $25 million worth of surrenders on Monday to $100 million worth
Thursday.;    "That type of increase and amount is an impossible situation for
the company," the insurance commissioner said.;    The state's first elected
insurance chief, noting that the brokerage Shearson Lehman Brothers owns 28
percent of First Capital's stock and sold 75 percent of its life insurance
policies from 1986 to this year, called on Shearson to shore up the firm.;   
'Ownership has its responsibilities';  "We would expect that Shearson Lehman
will accept the reality that ownership has its responsibilities," said
Garamendi, employing a twist on the slogan of Shearson's parent, American
Express: "Membership has its privileges.";    The state's action does not
preclude First Capital from honoring other insurance obligations such as death
benefits and annuities.;    Garamendi said "untimely stories in New York
newspapers" that state regulators were negotiating with American Express to
assist First Capital hastened the run by policyholders to cash in.;    "We
believe that in general the life insurance industry is a healthy industry,"
Garamendi said when asked if further failures are likely. "It is not in
similar circumstances as the savings and loan industry. It's an industry that
has a very high percentage of the companies operating in a sound and wise
financial manner.";     TROUBLE AT FIRST CAPITAL; After reports of First
Capital Life Insurance Co.'s financial plight set off a run of customers
trying to cash in their policies, the California Department of Insurance
stepped in Friday to keep the company afloat.; What's wrong with firm;
(box)Forty-six percent of its investments are in non-investment grade
securities -- 'junk bonds,' according to state Insurance Commissioner John
Garamendi.; (box)Operating costs -- twice the industry average -- were
elevated by "unusually high" fees charged by its parent, First Capital
Holdings, for asset management and other services, Garamendi said.;
(box)Reports that the firm was in trouble set off a groundswell of requests to
redeem policies -- $10 million a day last week, $25 million, Monday, $30
million, Tuesday, $60 million, Wednesday and $100 million, Thursday.; What
state ordered firm to do; (box)Stop issuing new policies.; (box)Stop making
loans secured by policies; (box)Stop making payments to its parent company or
its affiliates without permission from state regulators.; State's long-term
plan for firm; (box)Sell the company's universal life insurance business,
which has about $1.3 billion in assets.; (box)Reduce junk bond holdings to
less than 20 percent of its portfolio.; (box)Reduce operating costs.; (box)Get
cash infusion from American Express and its brokerage Shearson Lehman
Brothers, which own 28 percent of the parent company.; If you have a policy;
(box)The state's action does not preclude payment of death benefits and
annuities.; (box)Policyholders can call the state Department of Insurance
consumer hot line for information -- (800) 927-HELP.; Mercury News  </TEXT>
