<LP>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. -- Barely five months into the job,
California's first elected insurance commissioner, John
Garamendi, says he doesn't like the work.
   "It sure hasn't been fun," he told a group of insurance
underwriters recently. "I had no idea that the events and the
task would be so difficult."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Elected with a mandate to roll back auto insurance rates,
Mr. Garamendi, 46 years old, has instead become the warden of
the biggest insurance failures ever. Between them, Executive
Life Insurance Co. and First Capital Life Insurance Co. owe
more than $14 billion to holders of policies and annuities.
The shortfall in assets has yet to be determined.
   Mr. Garamendi's actions will mean a lot -- not only to
more than half a million policyholders across the nation but
to a life insurance industry undercut by public doubt. Should
he succeed in rehabilitating the failed companies and cutting
auto rates, industry experts say, the darkly handsome and
ambitious Mr. Garamendi will have transformed the obscure
post of state insurance commissioner into a seat of power and
a locus of political change.
   The size of the financial failures, the commissioner's
political skills and California's frequent role as a cradle
of political trends already have brought public recognition
and a potentially pivotal role in an emerging debate over the
direction of insurance regulation. "Mr. Garamendi could
become the prototype for more active insurance commissioners
around the country," says William O'Neill, vice president for
insurance rating services at Standard &amp; Poor's Corp.
   In an unusual step, the commissioner will meet today with
hundreds, perhaps thousands, of Executive Life policyholders
at a public gathering in Los Angeles. Few if any of his
fellow regulators would attend such a meeting "unless they
were dragged there," says James Long, insurance commissioner
of North Carolina and president of the National Association
of Insurance Commissioners, the overseer of the nation's
system of state regulation.
   For the moment, Mr. Garamendi has been able to blame the
downfall of Executive Life and of First Capital on his
predecessor, Roxani Gillespie, whose supervision he calls a
case of "Don't worry-be happy." Mr. Garamendi promises a
return of "the hard hand of regulation" to the U.S.'s largest
insurance market. Ms. Gillespie -- who like previous
California insurance commissioners and the top regulators in
38 other states was appointed by the governor -- defends her
actions as appropriate.
   Mr. Garamendi came to office in January under the terms of
Proposition 103, a November 1988 referendum that created the
elected commissionership and mandated sharply lower auto
insurance rates. The rates provision is forcefully opposed by
what the commissioner calls a "gang of 84" insurance
companies, which have taken the matter to court.
   By most standards, Mr. Garamendi, a former state
legislator, college football hero and wrestler, is an oddity
in the world of insurance regulation. He is a Harvard
Business School graduate who grew up in a well-heeled family
on a California ranch and now owns a pear orchard in Walnut
Grove, south of Sacramento. He has a populist style, is
comfortable with TV cameras and has a talent for catchy
phrases.
   When Ms. Gillespie approved a rash of rate increases only
days before she left office, Mr. Garamendi blasted it as a
"Christmas present to the fat-cat insurance companies." And
when American Express Co., with a 28% stake in the parent of
First Capital Life, resisted Mr. Garamendi's private requests
that it add cash to the beleaguered company, he publicly
charged American Express and its Shearson Lehman Brothers
investment unit with unseemly abandonment. "If membership has
its privileges, then ownership has its responsibilities," he
declared. American Express has said it will take appropriate
actions but hasn't accepted any obligation to recapitalize
the ailing company.
   His willingness to shoot from the lip has raised eyebrows
in the insurance business, where many worry that Mr.
Garamendi's stewardship of Executive Life, a Los
Angeles-based unit of First Executive Corp., and of First
Capital Life, a San Diego-based unit of First Capital
Holdings Corp., could be marred by rash actions. There also
is concern that the commissioner has created an unrealistic
wave of hope with his plans to resuscitate what appear to be
badly damaged companies.
   There has been one major slip. Mr. Garamendi announced his
conservatorship of Executive Life in optimistic tones, saying
that policy redemptions and loans would be blocked but that
routine death-benefit and annuity checks would continue at
100 cents on the dollar. But for nearly two weeks, claimants
were left hanging by a glitch in an Insurance Department
order. While death benefits are now being paid at 100 cents
on the dollar, annuity payments are being made at 70 cents.
The misstep irked regulators in many states.
   Mr. Garamendi has been guarded about a point of vital
interest to state regulators: the debate over what role, if
any, the federal government should play in the patchwork of
state insurance regulation. Though some industry and
regulatory people say the commissioner of the nation's most
populous state might break ranks and support federal
oversight, Mr. Garamendi says he wants to give state
regulation more time. But he suggests that more large
failures would change his mind. "The schedule is driven by
events," he says.
   Many who know him say Mr. Garamendi himself is driven. For
more than 15 years he was a state legislator, concentrating
on ecological and economic issues. "He was never a superstar
in the state Senate but was always extremely ambitious," says
Dick Rosengarten, publisher of Calfornia Political Week, a
newsletter.
   In 1982, Mr. Garamendi, then 37, ran in the Democratic
primary for governor and lost. Soon afterward, he tried to
unseat the president pro tem of the state Senate. "It was the
shortest-lived coup in history -- less than 36 hours," Mr.
Garamendi says of his defeat. He also lost a bid for the
nomination for state controller.
   But as commissioner, Mr. Garamendi has found the high
profile he has sought.
   "At the moment he's the most visible politician in
California," says Clinton Reilly, a California political
consultant who has advised Mr. Garamendi.
</TEXT>
