<LP>
   Mutual Benefit Life Insurance Co., the nation's
18th-largest life insurer, plans to sell off part of its
operations to boost its sagging capital.
   The Newark, N.J.-based company, hurt by sour real-estate
loans and investments, is readying the restructuring plan
after it held unsuccessful talks to receive a major infusion
of cash from Metropolitan Life Insurance Co. At one time, the
talks, which ended earlier this week, included a possible
merger between Met Life, the second-largest life insurer, and
Mutual Benefit, which has $13.5 billion in assets and 4.5
million policyholders. Met Life rejected both proposals.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   It is unclear how much capital Mutual Benefit is seeking.
Under the current restructuring, Mutual Benefit would sell
part of its group health business and withdraw from some
individual life insurance businesses, said Henry Kates,
president.
   Mutual Benefit is the latest life insurer to seek outside
capital because of losses in its real-estate investment
portfolio. Equitable Life Assurance Society of the United
States's board yesterday reviewed proposals from investors
for as much as $1 billion in new capital.
   USF&amp;G Corp., which also has had large real-estate losses,
said this week it wants to raise $300 million. Earlier this
month, regulators seized the main insurance units of First
Executive Corp. and First Capital Holdings Co. because of
junk-bond woes.
   The talks between Mutual Benefit Life and Metropolitan
centered on arrangements to conserve Mutual Benefit's capital
base, including a $100 million capital infusion as one
possibility, Mr. Kates said.
   All of the options would have brought relief for Mutual
Benefit, whose real-estate investment losses have helped
reduce total capital to $561 million at year end from $576
million a year earlier, according to figures from Townsend &amp;
Schupp, a Connecticut insurance consulting firm. The
portfolio includes more than $200 million invested in Fisher
Island, an exclusive resort in Florida.
   As a result, the company's capital as a percentage of
invested assets is well below the industry norm. And its low
capital and heavy concentration could lead to a downgrading
by rating agencies before it can implement its plan, which
Mr. Kates said hasn't been cleared by regulators.
   Mr. Kates stressed that the company isn't in any immediate
danger and doesn't have a pressing need for capital. Indeed,
a spokesman for the New Jersey Insurance Department said
regulators there hadn't taken any action against the insurer
but added that a routine examination of the company is under
way.
   Details of the restructuring plan are sketchy. Generally
it calls for transforming its individual life insurance
business into an agency business, with Mutual Benefit selling
the policies of other life insurers. It would still sell some
forms of life insurance, such as term insurance.
   The company then would concentrate on its group life
insurance business, which it would sell through a stock-owned
subsidiary of Mutual Benefit. Mutual Benefit, as a mutual
insurance company is owned by its policyholders. To raise
capital for the stock-owned unit, the company probably would
eventually sell stock either through a private placement or a
public offering, Mr. Kates said.
   The termination of talks with Met Life could result in a
downgrading of Mutual Benefit by Standard &amp; Poor's Corp. and
Moody's Investors Service Inc., which currently assign
double-A-plus and double-A-3 ratings respectively to the
company. Mr. Kates said both agencies are now evaluating the
situation. Insurance companies depend on high ratings to
maintain policyholder confidence and to retain top-producing
agents.
   Mutual Benefit has one of the largest real-estate
portfolios as a percentage of its assets among the large
insurance companies. At the end of the year, it had
foreclosed on more than 50%, or $226 million, of its
real-estate investments. Its nonperforming mortgage loans
climbed to $247 million from $112 million at the end of 1989.
Its total mortgage portfolio stood at $4.7 billion, according
to Townsend &amp; Schupp.
   As a result of its investment problems, unrealized capital
losses totaled $215 million at year end. Total capital, which
includes reserves for investments, fell to $561 million from
$576 million in 1989.
   Some analysts say much of the company's capital base was
generated through so-called surplus relief reinsurance, which
has come under fire recently by California Insurance
Commissioner John Garamendi. California regulators recently
charged that some kinds of surplus relief reinsurance pacts
artificially inflate capital.
   At the end of last year, Mutual Benefit arranged surplus
relief reinsurance agreements on life insurance involving
over $1 billion in premiums, according to John Kleiman, an
analyst with Hartford, Connecticut-based Conning &amp; Co. It is
unclear whether those agreements are the same type that Mr.
Garamendi has questioned.
   Mr. Kates, who called the transactions routine, said the
agreements generated $40 million in surplus. Without the
transactions, its total capital would have dipped to $521
million. "It certainly looks like a rush to shore up the
balance sheet at the end of the year," Mr. Kleiman said.
</TEXT>
