FINANCIAL, INSURANCE, MUTUAL FUNDS, ACCOUNTING, LEASING (FIN) </IN>
<DATELINE> LOS ANGELES  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First Capital Holdings Corp.'s plan to acquire the major insurance unit of E.F. Hutton Group Inc. for $300 million is being delayed, apparently because of questions raised by state insurance regulators. 

   First Capital, a holding company with life insurance and mutual-fund management units, previously told securities analysts and investors that it hoped to complete the acquisition of E.F. Hutton Insurance Group by the end of last month. 

   Yesterday, First Capital issued a statement saying it is "in continuing discussions with the California Insurance Department concerning the structure of its pending acquisition . . . and will grant the department a further extension of time to consider its application." 

   Officials of First Capital declined to elaborate on the statement except to say that the extension is for "a very limited" amount of time that the company wouldn't specify. 

   Roxani Gillespie, the California insurance commissioner, said in an interview that the insurance department has asked for more information from First Capital about the Hutton acquisition. 
She declined to specify the department's major areas of concern about the transaction. 
Asked if she expects the acquisition to be completed, she said that "it will all depend" on the information provided. 

   The acquisition can't be completed without the department's approval. 
The Hutton insurance unit is based in La Jolla, Calif., and is regulated by the California department. 

   Thomas G. Richter, an insurance analyst with Robinson-Humphrey Co. in Atlanta, said First Capital officials told him that the insurance department was concerned about the amount of debt that First Capital intends to incur to finance the acquisition. 

   Mr. Richter said First Capital officials "still feel that the deal is intact." 
However, he said First Capital may change its planned securities offering to include more preferred stock and less debt. 

   In March, First Capital filed registration statements with the Securities and Exchange Commission covering issues of $150 million of senior subordinated notes, $50 million of convertible debentures and $50 million of cumulative convertible preferred stock, all via Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. First Capital also has said it plans to borrow $200 million from banks to help finance the Hutton insurance acquisition. 

   First Capital and Drexel were scheduled to hold meetings to explain the securities offering to potential investors in New York, Boston and Chicago starting today, but the meetings were canceled yesterday. 

   First Capital shares fell $1 to close at $15.50 in New York Stock Exchange composite trading yesterday. 

   In a prospectus for the securities offering, First Capital said it would have $113 million in equity and $456 million in debt after the offering, Mr. Richter said. 
He noted that the indicated debt to equity ratio of about 4-to-1 was far greater than that of most life insurers, which typically have little or no debt. 

   Mr. Richter also noted that First Capital said in its prospectus that some of the proceeds of the offering would be used to pay interest on its debt. 

   Some investors have questioned First Capital's method of accounting for certain life insurance products. 
The company books about 17% of the expected future profits from certain policies in the year the policies are sold, rather than waiting until it earns the profits over several years, Mr. Richter said. 

   The acquisition of Hutton's insurance unit would add about $2.7 billion in assets to First Capital, which had total assets of $816 million at March 31. 
First Capital's major units currently are Fidelity Bankers Life Insurance Co., Richmond, Va., and Pilgrim Group Inc., which runs a group of mutual funds. 

</TEXT>
