<LEADPARA>  In a surprise move that jeopardizes life insurance and annuity payments to
thousands of individuals, the Internal Revenue Service has demanded $643
million in back taxes from Executive Life Insurance Co. of California,
insurance regulators said Monday.;    State Insurance Commissioner John
Garamendi said he would fight the IRS claim with every legal means available,
but if the IRS succeeds, it would force liquidation of the company's $10
billion in assets. That could spell financial ruin for hundreds of thousands
of holders of insurance policies and annuities, he said.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Business  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  IRS DEMANDS $643 MILLION FROM EXEC LIFE  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Mercury News Staff Writer Cris Oppenheimer-Pitthan contributed to this report.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     "This would wipe out whatever capital the company has," Garamendi said. "If
this company is liquidated, the pain will be enormous for policyholders,
annuitants and the whole life insurance industry.";    In a bit of good news,
Garamendi said the insurance department received court permission Monday to
resume payments on death benefits and annuities.;    The court order issued
Monday by the Los Angeles Superior Court allows Executive First -- under the
state's conservatorship -- to resume paying 100 percent of death benefits and
70 percent of retirement annuities to beneficiaries and policyholders. Annuity
holders, except those under guaranteed investment contracts, would receive
their current payments.;    If the IRS is successful in forcing its claims,
however, all payments may stop, Garamendi said.;    Executive Life, the
primary operating subsidiary of First Executive Corp. of Los Angeles, was
seized by California regulators on April 11 after defaults in its huge
portfolio of high-yield "junk bonds" left it in financially hazardous
condition and sent customers rushing to cash in policies.;    Last week,
regulators in New York seized the New York subsidiary for the same reasons.;  
 The actions amounted to the largest failure yet of an insurance company.;   
Californians hold about 34,000 Executive Life insurance policies with a face
value of $9.5 billion and 16,500 annuities valued at $725 million. Overall,
Executive has 170,000 life insurance policies worth $38 billion and 75,000
annuity contracts worth $2.5 billion in force in 46 states.;     Claims by the
Internal Revenue Service would take precedence over claims of policyholders
and all other creditors of the company, industry experts said.;    If the IRS
is successful in laying claim to the bulk of Executive Life's cash, Garamendi
said policyholders would need to look to state guarantee funds to pay their
claims. Each guarantee fund has separate limits on coverage.;    California's
fund covers up to 80 percent of the policy amount to a maximum of $100,000 on
annuities and $250,000 on death benefits. Less traditional products, such as
guaranteed investment contracts, are not covered at all.;    Moreover,
Garamendi noted that a previously announced rehabilitation plan, which
anticipated that the French company Altus Financial would buy Executive Life,
is also now in question because of the IRS claim.;    "Altus' proposal, and
the proposals we have received from other companies, do not include anything
for this tax liability," Garamendi said.;    The IRS claim is based on audits
of Executive Life's 1981, 1982 and 1983 tax years, according to regulators.
Although state Insurance Department officials knew that the IRS was reviewing
Executive Life's books regarding these years, until late last Friday the IRS
had refused to disclose the scope of their claim.;    But in a letter faxed
Friday afternoon to Executive Life, the federal agency said it is owed $643.4
million -- or roughly $249 million in taxes and $394 million in interest and
penalties. And it wants to be paid immediately.;    "It was not a coincidence
that the state takeover and our filing a lien on the insurer came within a few
days of each other," said IRS spokeswoman Jan Gribbon. "The law says that in
this kind of situation, a conservatorship, we must take action before the
assets are depleted."  </TEXT>
