<LP>
   California insurance regulators took over Western Pacific
Life Insurance Co., a little more than a week after Florida
regulators seized its parent company, which is now under
criminal investigation in Florida.
   The California order of conservatorship, granted by a
state court in Los Angeles last Tuesday, was sought because
of Western Pacific's financial instability resulting from a
portfolio of high-risk, high-yield bonds and the insolvency
of the parent, Guarantee Security Life Insurance Co., the
California insurance department said in announcing the
takeover on Friday.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The department declared a moratorium on Western Pacific
Life policy surrenders and loans, but said that full death
and annuity payments will continue.
   Western Pacific was found to be in "hazardous" condition
because of concerns about its junk-bond portfolio, the
insolvency of its parent company and the potential of an
increase in policy surrenders that could lead to a "run," the
California department said. At Dec. 31, Western Pacific had
assets of $46.7 million, of which 40% were invested in junk
bonds, the department said.
   Guarantee Security Life, Florida's sixth-largest life
insurance company, was seized by state regulators on Aug. 12
after the company admitted insolvency because of losses in
its junk-bond holdings. Executive offices of both Guarantee
Security Life and Western Pacific Life are in Jacksonville,
Fla., although Western Pacific Life is technically
headquartered in downtown Los Angeles.
   Paul Kiernan, vice president of marketing for both
companies, declined to comment directly on the regulators'
actions but said that "at the operating company level, we
didn't have any role in the management of the assets."
   Guarantee Security Life is a unit of Transmark USA Inc., a
holding firm owned or controlled by Mark Sanford, Mr. Kiernan
said. Mr. Sanford, a Jacksonville resident, couldn't be
reached for comment.
   Tom Gallagher, Florida treasurer and insurance
commissioner, recently disclosed that Guarantee Security Life
is the subject of a criminal investigation as to whether it
"relied on possibly illegal arrangements with stockbrokers
and accountants."
   On Friday, a Florida insurance department spokeswoman
said: "We have reason to believe that there is more to this
insolvency than just junk-bond investments. {But} the law
enforcement agencies that are investigating {violations} of
civil and criminal laws have asked us not to discuss this in
any way."
   At June 30, Western Pacific Life had 317 life insurance
policyholders and 3,717 annuitants, the California department
said. Guarantee Security Life had 51,739 annuities in force
with a net cash value of $410.4 million and 5,963
single-premium whole life insurance policies with a net cash
value of $134.7 million, the Florida department said. At one
time, as much as 90% of the company's assets were invested in
junk bonds, it said.
   Since California's first elected insurance commissioner,
John Garamendi, assumed office in January, he has put 16
insurance companies into receivership. The largest and most
visible was Executive Life Insurance Co., a junk-bond-laden
insurer that was seized in April. By contrast, Mr.
Garamendi's predecessor took control of seven companies in
1990 and 12 in 1989.
</TEXT>
