<CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Associated Press; John Garamendi addresses policyholders in Los
Angeles on Friday  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  CALIFORNIA; INSURANCE; COMPANY; CLOSING  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  Five hundred investors, fearing their life insurance and pension money is lost
to the junk bond craze, confronted California's top regulator Friday over the
collapse of Executive Life Insurance Co.;    John Garamendi, sworn in this
year as the state's first elected insurance commissioner, fielded questions
from emotional holders of policies, annuities and investment contracts in a
vast county meeting room.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Business  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  FIRST EXECUTIVE INVESTORS FACE GARAMENDI
ON COLLAPSE  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     He swore to protect them by quickly finding a buyer who will rebuild
Executive Life.;    And he listened to complaint after complaint: A man whose
handicapped daughter's annuity payments have been cut; a heart attack victim
who can't get insurance elsewhere but wonders if his premium payments "are
going into a hole"; investors whose requests to cash out policies are in
limbo.;    Of Executive Life's $10.1 billion in assets, $6.4 billion is
invested in junk bonds, by far the highest amount and proportion of any
insurer. The company boomed along with the junk bond market in the 1980s, but
suffered big losses when junk bond defaults multiplied and the market for them
went soft.;    Garamendi urged the investors to pressure legislators to stave
off federal tax demands on Executive Life. More than anything else, those
could annihilate the company before he can find a buyer willing to
rehabilitate it, he said.;    If the IRS collects $643 million in back taxes,
"it is a virtual certainty that we will have to liquidate" the company,"
Garamendi said. Liquidation would mean selling company assets without a ready
market, and the IRS would receive funds before policyholders, Garamendi said.;
   "I must tell you that liquidation is an unmitigated disaster for everyone,
particularly for you," Garamendi said.;    At present, Executive Life death
benefits are being paid in full. Annuities, contracts to provide income for
life or for a specified time, are being paid at 70 percent. Holders of
guaranteed investment contracts, more similar to bank certificate of deposits,
are being paid nothing.;    The meeting with the investors was the latest
high-profile move by the politically ambitious Garamendi, whose seizures of
Executive Life and fellow junk bond casualty First Capital Insurance have kept
him constantly in the public eye for the past month.;    Garamendi condemned
companies that replaced their pension plans with cheaper annuities offered by
Executive Life and other insurers.;    He said he would seek to hold the
employers responsible for making up the 30 percent that First Executive
annuitants have lost since the seizure. Some companies, such as Maxxam Corp.'s
Pacific Lumber, have offered to do so at least on a limited basis. Others,
such as food and tobacco giant RJR Nabisco, have refused to help.  </TEXT>
