<DESCRIPT>  CALIFORNIA; INSURANCE; RANKING; SURVEY; RESULT  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  Executive Life Insurance Co. led California's big life insurers in consumer
complaints in the year before its seizure by state regulators, according to a
survey released Wednesday.;    Overall, United Insurance of America, the 47th
largest company in the state, had the most complaints of the 50 life insurance
companies surveyed by the state Insurance Department.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  California News  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  SURVEY RATES INSURERS OF LIFE, HEALTH
RANKINGS BASED ON COMPLAINTS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  California News  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Transamerica Occidental Life had the fewest complaints of the top five life
insurance firms in 1990.;    Among the five largest health insurers in the
state, Aetna Life Insurance Co. had the most complaints settled against it
last year. Healthnet had the fewest.;    Insurance Commissioner John Garamendi
said he hoped the "test scores," would help consumers shop for the best deal
and encourage companies with the most complaints to "clean up their act.";   
He released the report a day after issuing a similar survey of auto and
homeowner insurers.;    "For those who failed their exams, they better shape
up, because there's going to be another exam next year," Garamendi told a
Capitol news conference.;    Survey is one test;  However, he cautioned that
consumers shouldn't judge companies solely on the survey but should also
consider firms' financial stability and policy prices.;    Garamendi called
United Insurance the "really bad news company in life insurance" with nine
times as many complaints as the industry average. A corporate executive, who
asked that his name be withheld, said he couldn't comment until he read the
survey.;    Five life insurers had zero complaints settled against them in
1990. They were Security Life of Denver, Standard Insurance, Aid Association
for Lutherans, Phoenix Mutual Life and Crown LIfe.;    Complaint leader; 
Among health insurers, Pioneer Life of Illinois, the 44th largest in
California, led overall in complaints with 15 times the industry average,
Garamendi said. Company officials had no immediate comment.;    Group Life
Insurance Co., the 31st biggest health insurance firm, had zero complaints.;  
 The survey ranked the companies by the number of complaints as compared with
policies written. To make the list, a complaint had to involve a violation of
insurance law or code, or come from a client who turned to the state only
after failing to get a response from an insurer.;    Two junk bond-laden
companies that were seized this spring by the state, Executive Life and First
Capital Life, ranked third and fourth in complaints among life insurers last
year.;    Garamendi said he would demand the companies to do better once they
get back on their feet.;    Executive Life, then the fourth largest in the
state, had 57 complaints, or .343 for every $1 million in premiums. First
Capital, then the 46th largest, had 11 complaints, or .308 per $1 million in
premiums.;    Leaders chastised;  Garamendi chastised Prudential Insurance of
America and Metropolitan Life Insurance Co., the first and third largest life
insurers in California, respectively, for ranking the eighth and ninth worst
in the survey.;    "As industry leaders, I expect them to lead in good service
as well as in sales," he said.;    Prudential received 94 complaints, or .227
per $1 million in premiums. Metropolitan 38 complaints, or .144 per $1 million
in premiums.;    Metropolitan also ranked ninth worst among health insurers,
with 49 complaints, or .413 per $1 million in premiums. " 'Get Met' is their
slogan. I suggest that if they don't improve their consumer service,
Californians will simply say, 'Met, nyet,' " Garamendi said.;    Insurer
disputes results;  MetLife spokesman Charles Sahner said he believes the
survey results for the company were artificially high. "Less than one-third of
1 percent of the millions of claims we pay each year result in a complaint,"
Sahner said in a statement released from the company's New York headquarters.;
   Last year, the Insurance Department investigated 1,197 complaints about
life insurance companies and 2,804 complaints involving health insurers,
Garamendi said. As a result, the agency recovered more than $5 million for
life insurance policyholders and $6.5 million from health insurance customers,
he said.  </TEXT>
