WHILE CUSTOMERS COULDN'T  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     Stern provided few details of the meeting but said the probe was part of an
ongoing investigation into operations of the San Diego-based insurer. She said
there is no criminal investigation so far.;    State Insurance Commissioner
John Garamendi ordered First Capital's funds frozen on May 10. Four days later
he seized the company and placed it under department conservatorship.;   
Thousands of First Capital policyholders tried to recover more than $265
million in assets in April and early May, following reports of its heavy
investment in junk bonds.;    But the insurer told them their requests would
take 30 days rather than the usual two weeks.;    Garamendi's May 10 order
prohibited policyholders from cashing out their policies and allowed the
company to honor only life insurance death benefits and payments for
annuities.;    Investigators are trying to determine whether Buck and Kelly
violated their positions of trust by using access and inside information to
unfair advantage over the company's other policyholders.;    The San Diego
Tribune reported on the investigation Wednesday.;    Charlie Perkins, a
spokesman for the company in New York, said Wednesday that First Capital
executives have been meeting regularly with state insurance officials since
the state seized the insurer.;    Perkins said he did not know the topic of
Wednesday's meeting and declined to comment further.;    First Capital has
$4.5 billion in assets and 260,000 policyholders.;    Garamendi has told the
Tribune his department is auditing First Capital's books and is investigating
whether any First Capital executives cashed their personal policies before the
state seizure.  </TEXT>
