<LP>
   New Jersey Life Insurance Co., already fighting off
seizure attempts by New Jersey regulators, was ordered by
California to stop writing and renewing policies.
   The California order comes as New Jersey seeks in court
today to take over New Jersey Life, which the state says is
insolvent and requires state intervention. The state won a
restraining order against the insurance company May 20, after
state examiners found what they believed to be a $36 million
deficit for New Jersey Life at the end of 1990. The state
said the company had claimed a $10 million surplus.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The restraining order expired at the end of May. A hearing
is scheduled today in state court in Hackensack, N.J., to
determine whether the company should be seized by the state.
New Jersey Life, based in Paramus, N.J., is challenging a
state takeover.
   According to the order issued by California Insurance
Commissioner John Garamendi against New Jersey Life, which
does 16% of its business in California, the company's
financial condition threatened to "render it insolvent" or
force it into liquidation. The stability of life insurance
contracts for 4,723 Californians was threatened, Mr.
Garamendi said.
   The 1990 annual statement filed by New Jersey Life with
California insurance regulators indicated a reserve credit of
$25.2 million for reinsurance ceded to RepublicVanguard Life
Insurance Co. under a "split co-insurance/modified
co-insurance" treaty. Mr. Garamendi recently said that such
treaties wouldn't be accepted in California because they
artificially inflate an insurer's capital levels.
   As a result, California said, New Jersey Life actually had
a $15.2 million deficit, putting the company below the
minimum capital and surplus needed to do business in
California. A hearing is scheduled for Aug. 16 in San
Francisco to determine whether the state will take further
action.
   California's actions didn't surprise New Jersey Life. "It
is not unexpected that several states would follow the
actions of New Jersey," said Richard Smith, a company
spokesman. Regarding the New Jersey court hearing, Mr. Smith
said, "We are not insolvent, and we are continuing to service
our policyholders, and the company is looking for an
opportunity to present the facts as we see them."
   As of Dec. 31, 1990, New Jersey Life had a total of $3.24
billion of insurance in force, of which $902 million was in
New Jersey. It currently has assets of $161 million.
</TEXT>
