<MEMO>  Mercury News Staff Writer Ken McLaughlin contributed to this report.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     He cited Executive Life's large junk-bond portfolio and insufficient
reserve capital. Of Executive Life's $10.1 billion in assets, about $6.4
billion is invested in high-risk, high-yield junk bonds, he said.;   
Garamendi said the Superior Court action was necessary to protect thousands of
people who have invested in the company.;    "These are the people who are
counting on this money -- and deservedly -- to enjoy and protect them for the
rest of their lives," Garamendi said.;    He added that Executive Life was
"fully cooperating in the transition.";    Bill Schulz, a spokesman for the
state Department of Insurance, said Executive Life would become "the largest
life insurance company ever to be placed under conservatorship" in the
country.;    Executive Life has 170,000 life insurance policies with a face
value of $38 billion, Garamendi said. Its parent, First Executive Corp., is a
$15 billion holding company which also operates Executive Life of New York.;  
 First Executive attracted customers during the booming '80s with low rates
made possible by high returns on junk bonds. First Executive's chairman, Fred
Carr, was the top customer of Michael Milken, the former Drexel Burnham
Lambert Inc. official who built an empire on junk bonds.;    Then the junk
bond market collapsed. Since the start of 1989, a quarter of First Executive's
junk bond portfolio has defaulted. As of last month, its $9 billion junk-bond
portfolio carried a market value of $6.7 billion.;    Earlier this month,
First Executive reported a loss of $465.9 million for the fourth quarter and
said California regulators had shut off the cash flow from its troubled
insurance units.;    Last week, New York regulators ordered Executive Life of
New York to stop writing new policies in the 23 states where it is licensed
and to immediately add $125 million to its reserves.;    California
regulators, fearing for Executive Life's solvency, barred the company from
making interest payments to the parent firm.;    Garamendi said he expects New
York regulators at some point will seize Executive Life of New York.;    Kevin
Foley, deputy superintendent of the New York State Insurance Department, said
his agency hasn't "made the final determination yet" about Executive Life's
solvency.;    The New York regulators are finishing an actuarial examination
of Executive Life and will "have a definitive statement" next week on the
insurer's condition, he said.  </TEXT>
