<LP>
   LOS ANGELES -- The two finalists in a court-supervised
auction for Executive Life Insurance Co. submitted sweetened
bids for the failed insurer, putting the process closer to a
scheduled Thursday decision by California's insurance
commissioner.
   The offers by a French investor group led by Altus
Finance, a subsidiary of the French bank Credit Lyonnais, and
by a group led by San Francisco investment bankers Hellman &amp;
Friedman advanced somewhat from earlier promises, reducing
prospective losses for some claimants.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   But the usual last-minute rush of bidding took an unusual
turn last night when the Hellman &amp; Friedman group tendered
their proposal nearly an hour after the court-imposed 4 p.m.
PST deadline, potentially invalidating the offer.
   A spokeswoman for California Insurance Commissioner John
Garamendi said no special approval was given for the late
filing and that the commissioner would simply note its time
of arrival to the California state court in Los Angeles that
is overseeing the auction.
   Mr. Garamendi is scheduled to announce a choice Thursday
between the two bids, which emerged as finalists in the
often-complicated three-month process. He will make a
recommendation to a California state court, which will have a
final say in the process. Several groups have already
suggested that they may challenge Mr. Garamendi's choice.
   Last week, the California insurance commissioner rejected
as too uncertain a bid mounted by the National Organization
of Life &amp; Health Guaranty Associations, representing
industry-funded state guaranty groups around the country. Mr.
Garamendi earlier had selected the bid provided its sponsors
were able to meet certain substantial conditions.
   Final concessions proposed by the French group would boost
initial recoveries by policyholders to just over 90 cents on
the dollar from 87 cents, the group said. Among other things,
the group increased to $3.55 billion the amount it proposes
to pay for most of Executive Life's junk bonds, a $250
million -- or 7.8% -- increase.
   As well, policyholders would be given greater flexibility
and lower policy lending rates, changes that the group values
at $75 million.
   Also offered was a chance for policyholders who remain
with the company to share in steep penalties paid by
policyholders who leave early. This concession, together with
a slight reduction in those penalties, would give a further
$500 million back to policyholders, the French group said.
   As previously reported, the French group's proposal is for
Altus Finance to buy most of Executive Life's junk bonds,
thus replacing the bonds with cash in the company's
portfolio. Thereafter, the continuing company, called Aurora,
would receive a further $300 million in new capital and would
be owned by a separate investor group headed by insurer
Mutuelle Assurance Artisanale de France.
   The group headed by Hellman &amp; Friedman, together with
Chicago investor Samuel Zell's Zell/Chilmark Fund L.P., Fund
American Cos. and the General Motors Corp. pension funds, has
proposed a different approach, planning to keep the junk
bonds in Executive Life with the argument that that structure
better enables policyholders to participate in gains from the
bonds.
   In yesterday's offer, the Hellman &amp; Friedman group said
they sweetened an earlier profit-sharing plan for
policyholders, provided greater access to funds for
policyholders through loans, and boosted certain crediting
rates.
   Executive Life Insurance Co., based in Los Angeles, was
seized in April by California regulators. Its Executive Life
Insurance Co. of New York was seized by regulators in that
state at the same time. The auction for the California unit
doesn't affect the New York companies. Both insurers were
units of First Executive Corp., which is now in Chapter 11
bankruptcy-law proceedings.
</TEXT>
