<LP>
   LOS ANGELES -- Eight offers for Executive Life Insurance
Co. were tendered before the deadline in a court-supervised
auction, but wrangling over the nation's second-largest
insurance failure is far from over.
   In a surprise, last-minute move, the French investor group
that has been the lead bidder with a formally negotiated
proposal filed more than a month ago substantially sweetened
its earlier offer.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   But there were no surprises among the bidders' names.
Notably absent were offers from any of the nation's largest
insurers. And though bids improved slightly in the final
rush, the proposals filed Friday by the 4 p.m. deadline would
leave billions of dollars in losses by Executive Life
claimants and the insurance industry's guaranty funds.
   Despite the auction's official close, those that formally
filed proposals can still sweeten or combine their offers, a
number of which were incomplete and apparently intended as
opening gambits. There's likely to be extensive last-minute
jockeying among bidders.
   "We expect this to be a vigorous two weeks," said a
spokesman for California Insurance Commissioner John
Garamendi, who is slated to make a choice by Oct. 25. Mr.
Garamendi's decision is subject to review by a state court in
Los Angeles that is overseeing Executive Life's legal
conservatorship. The company was seized in April by state
regulators.
   Proposals were received from both profit-minded investors
and groups with claims or interests in Executive Life. All
would continue Executive Life under a new name, with changes
in both its investment portfolio and obligations to
policyholders. Beyond that, however, the offers vary widely,
with some stripping Executive Life's vast junk bond portfolio
and others suggesting that the company can gain by retaining
the bonds rather than leaving gains from bankruptcy
reorganizations and sales to outside investors.
   The latest proposals now facing Mr. Garamendi and his
advisers are from the following groups:
   -- The French investor group headed by Altus Finance, a
subsidiary of the French bank Credit Lyonnais, and by insurer
Mutuelle Assurance Artisanale de France, which sweetened its
earlier bid, offering to buy most of Executive Life's vast
junk bond portfolio for $2.85 billion in cash -- a $150
million increase. The French insurer, known as MAAF, and its
partners said Friday that they would boost initial
policyholder values to 86 cents from the 81 cents offered
earlier and provide other concessions amounting to an added
value of $560 million to policyholders.
   -- Broad Inc., which said it would buy Executive Life's
insurance and annuity business. But the Los Angeles-based
insurer said it doesn't want Executive Life's junk bonds.
Broad hinted strongly it wants to supplant the French MAAF
group as Altus's partner, with Altus buying the junk bonds.
Otherwise, Broad said it has asked J.P. Morgan &amp; Co. to
finance some other buyer for the bonds. Part of its plan,
however, would leave the new Executive Life with a $2 billion
promissory note underwritten by the very bonds it wants to
sell.
   -- A Bondholder Protective Group, representing a portion
of the $1.85 billion of municipal bonds backed by Executive
Life funding agreements, and RRH Capital Management Inc., a
New York investment concern, which said they would retain the
junk bonds and restructure the company, among other things
issuing new securities to municipal bondholders. The
securities are intended to provide some return on bonds that
California regulators maintain rank behind all insurance
policies.
   -- A Bondholder Protective Committee, which asserted in a
letter of intent that it "reserved a bidding place" but
didn't offer any specifics. The committee represents the same
creditor class as the above group but is separate.
   -- A group comprising San Francisco investment bankers
Hellman &amp; Friedman; Zell-Chilmark Fund L.P., an investment
partnership headed by Chicago investor Samuel Zell; and Fund
American Cos., a Vermont-based investment concern, which
would keep Executive Life's junk bonds and recapitalize the
company with $300 million of cash and an added $450 million
of standby guaranties.
   -- The National Organization of Life and Health Guaranty
Associations, an industry-backed group representing state
insurance funds, which would retain the junk bonds and inject
$300 million in new capital in the form of guaranties from
industry-backed state guaranty funds. The proposal by Nolhga,
as the group is known, is intended to reduce the cost of
Executive Life's failure to its member funds.
   -- The Official Creditors' Committee for First Executive
Corp., the parent company of Executive Life that is in
Chapter 11 bankruptcy proceedings separate from the insurance
company's conservatorship, proposed a restructuring that it
said would pay policyholders 100 cents on the dollar, take
advantage of various tax angles and count on a divided
ownership of the apparently insolvent parent company roughly
equally with municipal bondholders.
   The bids filed assert that policyholders would initially
receive between 81 cents to 86 cents per dollar of policy
cash value.
   Executive Life's giant junk bond portfolio, which has set
the Los Angeles-based company apart from other insurers, is
the key variable in the salvage plans. The bonds, with a face
value close to $6.8 billion and some estimates of eventual
worth ranging above $4 billion, have widely been seen as a
source of hidden value. But Friday's bids revealed only
limited interest and financing for the portfolio. Altus alone
has offered cash for the bonds. The Broad and Rainwater group
bids have proposed intricate security swaps that would
continue to tie the company to the bonds.
   Offers by claimants and creditors, such as those by Nolhga
and the Bondholders' Protective Group, as well as the Hellman
&amp; Friedman bid, count on substantial gains from the junk
bonds and would retain them.
   But a California law signed just weeks ago may threaten
both plans that retain the bonds and those that "securitize"
them. The law limits the junk bond holdings of any insurer to
20% of assets -- a threshold exceeded by several plans.
   State Sen. Patrick Johnston, principal author of the bill,
in an interview, warned that statute seems to have been
ignored not only by would-be buyers of Executive Life but by
state insurance officials, who he said seem to be
backpedaling on the bill after earlier supporting it.
Complaining that "the ink is barely dry on the governor's
pen, the state senator said "it would be ironic indeed that
someone breached the standard immediately to clean up
Executive Life, the worst perpetrator of junk bond abuses."
   In addition to the junk bonds, California insurance
commissioner Garamendi and his advisers will have to consider
dozens of details relating to the complexities of Executive
Life's insurance policies and annuity contracts.
</TEXT>
